{"title_page": "The Brain Leeches", "text_new": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Brain Leeches\n| image          = \n| alt            = \n| director       = [[Fred Olen Ray]]\n| producer       = Fred Olen Ray\n| writer         = Jim Kennedy<br>[[Brad Linaweaver]]<br>Fred Olen Ray\n| based on       = \n| starring       = Paul Jones<br>Marcia Scott<br>Ray Starr\n| music          = Paul Jones<br>Sugar Lee<br>[[Modest Mussorgsky]]\n| cinematography = Marvin Levine<br>John Raber<br>Fred Olen Ray<br><small>(as Fred Ray)</small>\n| editing        = \n| studio         = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = \n| runtime        = 55 minutes\n| country        = \n| language       = English\n| budget         = $298.00\n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''The Brain Leeches''''' is an [[low-budget film|low-budget]]  [[science fiction film|science fiction]] [[exploitation film]] directed by [[Fred Olen Ray]] and starring Paul Jones, Marcia Scott & Ray Starr. It has a running time of 55 minutes, and was completed on a budget of $298.00. The film was shown publicly only once, although it has since become available through distributors. The project proved to be a turning point in the careers of two of the principals.\n\n==Plot==\nA former nuclear scientist turned pro-wrestler does battle with invading aliens who are taking over the brains of folks in a small town.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" />\n\n==Production==\n===Watershed moment===\nThe project proved to be a [[Tipping point (sociology)|watershed moment]] for two of the principals. Political essayist [[Brad Linaweaver]] received his first original story credit (for film) for ''The Brain Leeches''. The experience changed the trajectory of Linaweaver's career path, emphasizing film and science fiction writing for the rest of his life.<ref name=\"Investigator\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodinvestigator.com/2007/linaweaver.htm|title=Libertarian Screenwriter Brad Linaweaver Slams Neocons|publisher=Hollywood Investigator|date=August 12, 2007|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Memorium\">{{citeweb|url= https://amazingstories.com/2019/09/in-memoriam-brad-linaweaver/|title=In Memoriam-Brad Linaweaver|publisher=AmazingStories.com|date=September 12, 2019|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Locus\">{{cite web|url=https://locusmag.com/2019/09/brad-linaweaver-1952-2019/|title=Brad Linaweaver (1952-2019)|publisher=Locus Publications|date=September 3, 2019|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>  The film also jump started the career of prodigious Hollywood director/producer (and sometimes professional wrestler<ref name=\"Boggs2014\">{{cite book|author=Johnny D. Boggs|title=Jesse James and the Movies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-TLXYhM3cTkC&pg=PA225|date=10 January 2014|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-8496-6|page=225}}</ref>) Fred Olen Ray, who is also known for having loaned [[Quentin Tarantino]] his first 16mm camera to make ''[[My Best Friend's Birthday]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2007/film/news/q-a-with-tarantino-when-he-was-mr-green-1117961178/|title=Q&A with Tarantino\u2026when he was Mr. Green|first=Steve|last=Gaydos|website=Variety|date=14 March 2007|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The association and collaboration between Linaweaver and Ray continued until Linaweaver's death in 2019.<ref name=\"Locus\" />\n\n===Low-budget===\nPrincipal photography took place in 1978.<ref name=\"OS\" /> The film was shot using an old [[Auricon|Auricon 16mm camera]], and (expired) nine-year-old [[black and white]] film stock obtained from Ray's employer, an [[Orlando, Florida]] television station.<ref name=\"Ray1991\">{{cite book|author=Fred Olen Ray|title=The New Poverty Row: Independent Filmmakers as Distributors|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H9GknfDYd4sC&pg=PA176|date=1 January 1991|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-89950-628-9|page=176}}</ref><ref name=\"Quarles2010\">{{cite book|author=Mike Quarles|title=Down and Dirty: Hollywood's Exploitation Filmmakers and Their Movies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L5iRMlzjbSEC&pg=PA80|date=21 June 2010|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-6257-5|page=80}}</ref> The alien invaders were represented by large rubber ants, purchased at a [[dime store]] for 19 cents each.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /><ref name=\"Ants\">{{cite newspaper|url=https://orlandosentinel.newspapers.com/clip/16774509/the-brain-leeches/|title=An eye for an eye|publisher=[[The Orlando Sentinel]]|date=June 11, 1978|page=388|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Earthlings under mind control by the aliens were portrayed as having all-white eyes. The [[special effect]] was achieved by applying white tape to the actors' eyelids.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /> The destruction of the alien headquarters (the TV station where Ray worked) was depicted using stock footage of a nuclear explosion, from an old 16mm documentary found in the television station film archive.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /> The film score is a [[public domain]] recording of [[Moussorgsky]]'s [[Pictures at an Exhibition]], taken directly from a \"cheap record album\". According to Ray: \"No effort was made to synchronize any of the music to the picture\".<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /> Portions of the film were shot at a bar (The Foxhead Tavern) in Orlando.<ref name=\"OS\">{{cite newspaper|url=https://orlandosentinel.newspapers.com/clip/16774450/the-brain-leeches/|title=\"The Brain Leeches\"|publisher=[[The Orlando Sentinel]]|page=133|date=May 28, 1978|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> \n\nProduction of ''The Brain Leeches'' was completed, on budget, for $298.00.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /><ref name=\"Quarles2010\"/>\n\n==Distribution==\nIn 1991, Ray stated that ''The Brain Leeches'' had been shown publicly only one time, and that it would never be released for distribution.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /> However, more than 30 years after its first showing, copies of the film have become available through distributors such as Sinister Cinema.com.<ref name=\"Locus\"/><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.sinistercinema.com/product.asp?specific=33963|title=Sci Fi Brain Leeches, The*|publisher=Sinister Cinema.com|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cast==\n*Paul Jones as Dr. John Hayes\n*Marcia Scott as Susan\n*Ray Starr as Rusty Fender\n*Jennifer Knight as Rose\n*[[Brad Linaweaver]] as Billy Johnson\n*[[Fred Olen Ray]] (as Brian Wolfe) as Tom<ref name=\"Ants\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*''[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0075780/?ref_=fn_al_tt_1 The Brain Leeches]'' at [[Internet Movie Database]]\n*''[http://movies.msn.com/movies/movie/the-brain-leeches/ The Brain Leeches]'' at Movies.msn.com\n\n{{Fred Olen Ray}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brain Leeches}}\n[[Category:1970s science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Fred Olen Ray]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction horror films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox film\n| name           = The Brain Leeches\n| image          = \n| alt            = \n| director       = [[Fred Olen Ray]]\n| producer       = Fred Olen Ray\n| writer         = Jim Kennedy<br>[[Brad Linaweaver]]<br>Fred Olen Ray\n| based on       = \n| starring       = Paul Jones<br>Marcia Scott<br>Ray Starr\n| music          = Paul Jones<br>Sugar Lee<br>[[Modest Mussorgsky]]\n| cinematography = Marvin Levine<br>John Raber<br>Fred Olen Ray<br><small>(as Fred Ray)</small>\n| editing        = \n| studio         = \n| distributor    = \n| released       = \n| runtime        = 55 minutes\n| country        = \n| language       = English\n| budget         = $298.00\n| gross          = \n}}\n\n'''''The Brain Leeches''''' is an [[low-budget film|low-budget]]  [[science fiction film|science fiction]] [[exploitation film]] directed by [[Fred Olen Ray]] and starring Paul Jones, Marcia Scott & Ray Starr. It has a running time of 55 minutes, and was completed on a budget of $298.00. The film was shown publicly only once, although it has since become available through distributors. The project proved to be a turning point in the careers of two of the principals.\n\n==Plot==\nA former nuclear scientist turned pro-wrestler does battle with invading aliens who are taking over the brains of folks in a small town.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" />\n\n==Production==\n===Watershed moment===\nThe project proved to be a [[Tipping point (sociology)|watershed moment]] for two of the principals. Political essayist [[Brad Linaweaver]] received his first original story credit (for film) for ''The Brain Leeches''. The experience changed the trajectory of Linaweaver's career path, emphasizing film and science fiction writing for the rest of his life.<ref name=\"Investigator\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodinvestigator.com/2007/linaweaver.htm|title=Libertarian Screenwriter Brad Linaweaver Slams Neocons|publisher=Hollywood Investigator|date=August 12, 2007|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Memorium\">{{citeweb|url= https://amazingstories.com/2019/09/in-memoriam-brad-linaweaver/|title=In Memoriam-Brad Linaweaver|publisher=AmazingStories.com|date=September 12, 2019|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Locus\">{{cite web|url=https://locusmag.com/2019/09/brad-linaweaver-1952-2019/|title=Brad Linaweaver (1952-2019)|publisher=Locus Publications|date=September 3, 2019|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>  The film also jump started the career of prodigious Hollywood director/producer (and sometimes professional wrestler<ref name=\"Boggs2014\">{{cite book|author=Johnny D. Boggs|title=Jesse James and the Movies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-TLXYhM3cTkC&pg=PA225|date=10 January 2014|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-8496-6|page=225}}</ref>) Fred Olen Ray, who is also known for having loaned [[Quentin Tarantino]] his first 16mm camera to make ''[[My Best Friend's Birthday]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2007/film/news/q-a-with-tarantino-when-he-was-mr-green-1117961178/|title=Q&A with Tarantino\u2026when he was Mr. Green|first=Steve|last=Gaydos|website=Variety|date=14 March 2007|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> The association and collaboration between Linaweaver and Ray continued until Linaweaver's death in 2019.<ref name=\"Locus\" />\n\n===Low-budget===\nPrincipal photography took place in 1978.<ref name=\"OS\" /> The film was shot using an old [[Auricon|Auricon 16mm camera]], and (expired) nine-year-old [[black and white]] film stock obtained from Ray's employer, an [[Orlando, Florida]] television station.<ref name=\"Ray1991\">{{cite book|author=Fred Olen Ray|title=The New Poverty Row: Independent Filmmakers as Distributors|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=H9GknfDYd4sC&pg=PA176|date=1 January 1991|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-89950-628-9|page=176}}</ref><ref name=\"Quarles2010\">{{cite book|author=Mike Quarles|title=Down and Dirty: Hollywood's Exploitation Filmmakers and Their Movies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L5iRMlzjbSEC&pg=PA80|date=21 June 2010|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-6257-5|page=80}}</ref> The alien invaders were represented by large rubber ants, purchased at a [[dime store]] for 19 cents each.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /><ref name=\"Ants\">{{cite newspaper|url=https://orlandosentinel.newspapers.com/clip/16774509/the-brain-leeches/|title=An eye for an eye|publisher=[[The Orlando Sentinel]]|date=June 11, 1978|page=388|accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Earthlings under mind control by the aliens were portrayed as having all-white eyes. The [[special effect]] was achieved by applying white tape to the actors' eyelids.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /> The destruction of the alien headquarters (the TV station where Ray worked) was depicted using stock footage of a nuclear explosion, from an old 16mm documentary found in the television station film archive.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /> The film score is a [[public domain]] recording of [[Moussorgsky]]'s [[Pictures at an Exhibition]], taken directly from a \"cheap record album\". According to Ray: \"No effort was made to synchronize any of the music to the picture\".<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /> Portions of the film were shot at a bar (The Foxhead Tavern) in Orlando.<ref name=\"OS\">{{cite newspaper|url=https://orlandosentinel.newspapers.com/clip/16774450/the-brain-leeches/|title=\"The Brain Leeches\"|publisher=[[The Orlando Sentinel]]|page=133|date=May 28, 1978|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> \n\nProduction of ''The Brain Leeches'' was completed, on budget, for $298.00.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /><ref name=\"Quarles2010\"/>\n\n==Distribution==\nIn 1991, Ray stated that ''The Brain Leeches'' had been shown publicly only one time, and that it would never be released for distribution.<ref name=\"Ray1991\" /> However, more than 30 years after its first showing, copies of the film have become available through distributors such as Sinister Cinema.com.<ref name=\"Locus\"/><ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.sinistercinema.com/product.asp?specific=33963|title=Sci Fi BRAIN LEECHES, THE*|publisher=Sinister Cinema.com|accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref>  \n\n==Cast==\n*Paul Jones as Dr. John Hayes\n*Marcia Scott as Susan\n*Ray Starr as Rusty Fender\n*Jennifer Knight as Rose\n*[[Brad Linaweaver]] as Billy Johnson\n*[[Fred Olen Ray]] (as Brian Wolfe) as Tom<ref name=\"Ants\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*''[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0075780/?ref_=fn_al_tt_1 The Brain Leeches]'' at [[Internet Movie Database]]\n*''[http://movies.msn.com/movies/movie/the-brain-leeches/ The Brain Leeches]'' at Movies.msn.com\n\n{{Fred Olen Ray}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brain Leeches}}\n[[Category:1970s science fiction horror films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Fred Olen Ray]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American science fiction horror films]]\n", "name_user": "Gulbenk", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDistribution", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Brain_Leeches"}
